text: I saw this trailer before Deadpool 2 and I honestly must have been the only person in the theater not laughing. It just felt cringey to me, especially the last part. From this trailer alone, I don't think the juxtaposition of childhood images and vulgar tropes will work very well. It's been done before, successfully, since the dawn of adult animation. But here, it just seems like it's a bandwagon attempt, and it just made me feel uncomfortable. I don't really need to see a puppet ejaculating silly string for ten minutes.

text: The first 20 seconds had me interested, even with McCarthy as the lead, then the rest of the trailer lost me and made me not interested.   Why does everything comedy based have to be so forced these days?? The muppet aspect of this is what looks great, as I've always had an appreciation for movies like Cool World, Roger Rabbit, and of course the muppet movies, movies that incorporate the fantasy into reality. However, the humor looks mostly too over the top and forced. Who writes this stuff?   Did someone really think it would be funny to anyone to have a muppet ejaculating all over the place and to that extent? It's dumb and trying too hard, not actually funny. It's like a somewhat funny joke not knowing when to end or how to end, and that's why most comedies today suck.

text: I REALLY hope this is just another case of bad marketing trying WAY to hard to be edgy, because this trailer is AWEFUL. All it is is the "look, we're kind of from your childhood, but now we're R-rated, with a very bland story." Don't get me wrong, I think Mellissa McCarthy makes a great funny cop (I love The Heat and own it on DVD). However, "I look like I belong in a children's film but I'm really crude and R-rated" is only funny the first 2 times and is not enough to make an entire film around (just look at Ted, a movie that's just "look, I'm a teddy bear that drinks and swears"), but it can be cleaver if the story actually utilizes the fact that they're not humans for more than just sight gags (like in Ted 2, where Ted and society has to figure out if Ted is human or property).

text: What is this? The brand new "Sausage Party"?   Seriously, I would like to say that, if Jim Hensen actually saw this, I bet that he would actually like it, but only to a certain extent. I mean, looking back at early projects he did, it could be inferred that he actually enjoyed this sort of humor. If he didn't, he wouldn't have made extremely violent commercials for Wilkins Coffee back in the day. Also, even though this movie seems to be pretty raunchy, there are some saving graces for it, as can be seen in the trailer. One of them being the way that the puppets are being controlled. For example, the way they walked across the street in the beginning of the trailer. You can actually see them walking! How did they do that? How did they not use CGI for that? Also, Melissa McCarthy is in it too, and she's freaking awesome! And another saving grace for this is that no matter how hard they try, this will never be on the same level of disturbance as the infamous "Dark Crystal". Because that movie is even more creepy than this! And this is supposed to be a parody. It's not supposed to be taken seriously. Chill out, people. All in all, if you do watch it, please make sure you are actually ready to watch it, make sure there are no children nearby, and if it really is too disturbing for you, please turn your TV off and contact your local therapist and/or counselor. Thank you.
